definition: "C-peptide (connecting peptide) is a short polypeptide released by pancreatic beta cells in equimolar quantities with insulin during the processing of proinsulin. When the pancreas manufactures insulin, it first produces a single-chain precursor molecule — proinsulin — which is cleaved into insulin and C-peptide in a 1:1 ratio before secretion. Both are released into the portal circulation simultaneously. Because C-peptide and insulin are produced in exactly equal amounts but have different clearance rates — C-peptide has a longer half-life (approximately 30 minutes versus 5 minutes for insulin) and is cleared by the kidneys rather than the liver — C-peptide provides a more stable and accurate measure of total insulin secretion than insulin itself. Crucially, C-peptide is not present in exogenous insulin preparations, making it the only way to measure endogenous insulin production in people who inject insulin."
why_it_matters: "Fasting insulin is widely used in longevity medicine as a marker of insulin resistance — with good reason. But fasting insulin has a significant limitation: its measurement is affected by hepatic insulin extraction (the liver clears approximately 50% of insulin from portal blood before it reaches peripheral circulation), making the serum level an indirect reflection of pancreatic output. C-peptide is not extracted by the liver, so it provides a more direct and accurate measure of actual insulin secretion from the pancreas. In practice, this distinction matters most in two clinical scenarios. First, C-peptide distinguishes insulin resistance (where the pancreas is overproducing insulin to overcome resistance — high C-peptide) from beta cell exhaustion (where years of metabolic stress have depleted the pancreas's secretory capacity — low or falling C-peptide). This distinction has major implications for prognosis: a person with high fasting insulin but preserved beta cell function has a different trajectory and different intervention options than someone with declining beta cell output. Second, C-peptide is the definitive marker for tracking metabolic recovery — as insulin resistance improves with diet, exercise, and weight loss, C-peptide falls toward normal, confirming that the pancreas is doing less work."

